June 28 2026 — I Accidentally Became an Open Source Contributor (Kind Of)

So today I decided to contribute to freeCodeCamp. A project used by millions. No big deal. 👀

What I did:
- Searched a massive codebase for spelling errors in code comments
- Found gems like searcn (search), fuffill (fulfill))
- Learned that collapsable is not a word. It's collapsible. English is hard.

What I thought the workflow was:

▎ Fork → Fix → PR → Fame

What the workflow actually is:

▎ Fork → Fix → PR → Bot yells at you 😭 → Create issue → Wait → Update PR → Pray 🙏

Things I learned:
1. Always create a GitHub issue before opening a PR — even for tiny fixes. The bot WILL find you.
2. Branch names matter — fix/spelling-in-comments > comment-typos. Professionalism is a vibe.
3. Commit messages follow a format: fix(scope): description — not just "fixed stuff"
4. Open source is 10% coding, 90% reading contribution guidelines you didn't read the first time

Current status: Issue open. PR waiting. Fingers crossed. 🤞
First PR is always the scariest. But I took the first step.
